WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.930 --> 00:00:05.930
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good evening.

00:00:05.930 --> 00:00:06.930
I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:00:06.930 --> 00:00:09.160
On the "NewsHour" tonight: Brexit in the balance.

00:00:09.160 --> 00:00:14.789
The U.K. Parliament rejects Prime Minister
May's latest plan to leave the European Union

00:00:14.789 --> 00:00:16.730
at the end of the month.

00:00:16.730 --> 00:00:18.940
Then: grounding the fleet.

00:00:18.940 --> 00:00:26.190
The U.S. continues to permit the Boeing 787
MAX jets to fly, as Europe and others countries

00:00:26.190 --> 00:00:28.590
ban them from the skies.

00:00:28.590 --> 00:00:30.710
And varsity blues.

00:00:30.710 --> 00:00:36.460
Dozens of parents and coaches are indicted,
after a federal investigation into widespread

00:00:36.460 --> 00:00:39.860
college admissions fraud at elite universities.

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:46.230
Plus, we return to the southern border, this
time in Mexico, to examine the harsh conditions

00:00:46.230 --> 00:00:51.050
and uncertainty faced by migrant families
waiting to enter the U.S. legally.

00:00:51.050 --> 00:00:54.990
MARTIN SALGADO AMES, Director, Casa del Migrante
(through translator): Until a few months ago,

00:00:54.990 --> 00:00:59.030
the majority of the population that came to
this shelter were men, mainly men.

00:00:59.030 --> 00:01:03.710
But this started to change drastically when
violence and unemployment started to increase.

00:01:03.710 --> 00:01:05.479
Then entire families started crossing.

00:01:05.480 --> 00:01:09.040
JUDY WOODRUFF: All that and more on tonight's
"PBS NewsHour."

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:20.920
(BREAK)

00:01:20.920 --> 00:01:25.710
JUDY WOODRUFF: Britain's Parliament has issued
a stunning new statement on Brexit tonight:

00:01:25.710 --> 00:01:30.150
It won't buy the prime minister's plan to
leave the European Union.

00:01:30.150 --> 00:01:37.320
What it will buy instead is anything but clear,
after rejecting her plan by nearly 150 votes.

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:39.900
Special correspondent Ryan Chilcote reports
from London.

00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:43.320
THERESA MAY, British Prime Minister: If this
vote is not passed tonight, if this deal is

00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:45.650
not passed, then Brexit could be lost.

00:01:45.650 --> 00:01:50.540
RYAN CHILCOTE: The future of Britain's exit
from the European Union was on the line in

00:01:50.540 --> 00:01:55.409
day-long debate, as was Prime Minister Theresa
May's political career.

00:01:55.409 --> 00:02:01.060
May spoke with a hoarse voice that underscored
her exhaustion from a last-ditch effort to

00:02:01.060 --> 00:02:03.290
push her amended Brexit deal through Parliament.

00:02:03.290 --> 00:02:09.530
THERESA MAY: I believe it is absolutely imperative
for this House that we meet the decision that

00:02:09.530 --> 00:02:16.219
was taken by the British people in June 2016,
that we deliver on that referendum, and that

00:02:16.219 --> 00:02:18.099
we deliver Brexit for the British people.

00:02:18.099 --> 00:02:24.029
RYAN CHILCOTE: Her original Brexit plan suffered
a resounding defeat by a historic margin back

00:02:24.029 --> 00:02:25.040
in January.

00:02:25.040 --> 00:02:30.849
MAN: The ayes to the right 242, the no's to
the left 432.

00:02:30.849 --> 00:02:35.739
RYAN CHILCOTE: With that weighing on her mind,
the prime minister made an 11th-hour trip

00:02:35.739 --> 00:02:40.629
to Strasbourg, France, last night to seek
new concessions from the European Commission's

00:02:40.629 --> 00:02:41.629
president.

00:02:41.629 --> 00:02:46.249
They reached legally binding changes on one
of the deal's main sticking points: the so-called

00:02:46.249 --> 00:02:51.749
Irish backstop that would ensure the border
between E.U. member Ireland and the United

00:02:51.749 --> 00:02:55.999
Kingdom's Northern Ireland remains open after
Brexit.

00:02:55.999 --> 00:03:01.219
Britain's objective: for the U.K. not to be
tied to the E.U. and its trade rules indefinitely,

00:03:01.219 --> 00:03:06.809
should they be unable to agree on the nature
of their future relationship.

00:03:06.809 --> 00:03:11.519
Right now, the border between Northern Ireland
and the Republic of Ireland is all but invisible.

00:03:11.519 --> 00:03:14.260
That means cars and goods can cross freely.

00:03:14.260 --> 00:03:17.620
May's original Brexit strategy would have
kept that border open.

00:03:17.620 --> 00:03:21.689
THERESA MAY: A joint instrument with comparable
legal weight to the withdrawal agreement will

00:03:21.689 --> 00:03:26.239
guarantee that the E.U. cannot act with the
intent of applying the backstop indefinitely.

00:03:26.239 --> 00:03:29.510
RYAN CHILCOTE: But that assurance also came
with a warning

00:03:29.510 --> 00:03:34.719
JEAN-CLAUDE JUNCKER, President, European Commission:
In politics, sometimes you get a second chance.

00:03:34.719 --> 00:03:40.849
It is what we do with this second chance that
counts, because there will be no third chance.

00:03:40.849 --> 00:03:45.839
There will be no further interpretation of
the interpretations, and no further assurances

00:03:45.839 --> 00:03:46.969
of the reassurances.

00:03:46.969 --> 00:03:51.939
RYAN CHILCOTE: Then, this morning, Britain's
attorney general, Geoffrey Cox, took the wind

00:03:51.939 --> 00:03:58.449
out of May's sails, issuing a legal assessment
that the changes reduce, but do not eliminate

00:03:58.449 --> 00:04:02.319
the risk the U.K. could remain trapped in
a trade union with the E.U.

00:04:02.319 --> 00:04:07.670
GEOFFREY COX, U.K. Attorney General: The question
for the House is whether, in the light of

00:04:07.670 --> 00:04:16.820
these improvements, as a political judgment,
the House should now enter into those arrangements.

00:04:16.820 --> 00:04:24.460
However, the matters of law affecting withdrawal
can only inform what is essentially a political

00:04:24.460 --> 00:04:27.199
decision that each of us must make.

00:04:27.199 --> 00:04:32.530
RYAN CHILCOTE: The magnitude of that political
decision fueled passionate debate in Parliament.

00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:36.659
MAN: The honorable gentleman's cheeky, chappy
chortling and chuckling away from a sedentary

00:04:36.659 --> 00:04:39.930
position, but it's been made perfectly clear
that the prime minister's not giving way.

00:04:39.930 --> 00:04:43.560
RYAN CHILCOTE: Opposition Labor Party leader
Jeremy Corbyn was among those who rejected

00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:44.560
the deal.

00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:47.520
JEREMY CORBYN, Leader, Labor Party: After
three months of running down the clock, the

00:04:47.520 --> 00:04:54.229
prime minister has, despite very extensive
delays, achieved not a single change to the

00:04:54.229 --> 00:04:55.880
withdrawal agreement.

00:04:55.880 --> 00:04:58.259
Not one single word has changed.

00:04:58.259 --> 00:05:02.229
RYAN CHILCOTE: Opponents again zeroed in on
the so-called Irish backstop.

00:05:02.229 --> 00:05:06.409
MAN: If, in December 2020, alternate arrangements
aren't found for the backstop, we will have

00:05:06.409 --> 00:05:10.030
a hotel California Brexit, where we will have
checked out, but we won't be leaving.

00:05:10.030 --> 00:05:14.490
RYAN CHILCOTE: And, critically, many of May's
own allies, like Northern Ireland's Democratic

00:05:14.490 --> 00:05:18.479
Unionist Party, refused to support the divorce
agreement.

00:05:18.479 --> 00:05:24.129
With her coalition crumbling around her, Prime
Minister May's Brexit strategy failed to win

00:05:24.129 --> 00:05:25.129
passage.

00:05:25.129 --> 00:05:31.009
MAN: The ayes to the right 242, the no's to
the left 391.

00:05:31.009 --> 00:05:32.410
So the no's have it.

00:05:32.410 --> 00:05:34.560
The no's have it.

00:05:34.560 --> 00:05:39.470
RYAN CHILCOTE: This evening, Prime Minister
May voiced her own frustration after the fateful

00:05:39.470 --> 00:05:40.470
vote.

00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:44.169
THERESA MAY: I profoundly regret the decision
that this House has taken tonight.

00:05:44.169 --> 00:05:49.009
I continue to believe that by far the best
outcome is that the United Kingdom leaves

00:05:49.009 --> 00:05:53.610
the European Union in an orderly fashion with
a deal.

00:05:53.610 --> 00:05:57.900
RYAN CHILCOTE: As for the European Union and
its leaders, they're saying, look, there have

00:05:57.900 --> 00:05:59.760
been months and months of negotiations.

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:05.229
The U.K. decided to leave the European Union
two-and-a-half years ago.

00:06:05.229 --> 00:06:10.880
They're holding firm, and they're saying they're
not going to renegotiate the terms of the

00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:13.130
U.K.'s exit from the E.U.

00:06:13.130 --> 00:06:14.130
-- Judy.

00:06:14.130 --> 00:06:16.389
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Ryan, what a spectacle.

00:06:16.389 --> 00:06:17.490
Tell us what's next.

00:06:17.490 --> 00:06:23.030
RYAN CHILCOTE: Well, tomorrow, the Parliament
is going to vote on whether the U.K. should

00:06:23.030 --> 00:06:27.449
exit the European Union without a deal with
the E.U.

00:06:27.449 --> 00:06:30.150
She doesn't think that's a good idea.

00:06:30.150 --> 00:06:35.110
That said, there are people who support Brexit
that think it's a good idea, that actually

00:06:35.110 --> 00:06:39.580
the U.K. would have more autonomy to pursue
the kind of trade deals it would like the

00:06:39.580 --> 00:06:40.580
pursue.

00:06:40.580 --> 00:06:45.690
Now, if that didn't get supported, if the
parliamentarians say, no, we do have to have

00:06:45.690 --> 00:06:50.860
a deal, then on Thursday, they will have another
vote where they will be asked whether the

00:06:50.860 --> 00:06:55.819
deadline, the March 29 deadline, when the
U.K. is supposed to leave the E.U., whether

00:06:55.819 --> 00:06:58.919
that should be extended, pushed back.

00:06:58.919 --> 00:07:02.840
So, two more votes coming quite possibly this
week.

00:07:02.840 --> 00:07:06.349
JUDY WOODRUFF: And so, Ryan, I know there
are a number of directions this could go,

00:07:06.349 --> 00:07:08.360
but what are the options after this?

00:07:08.360 --> 00:07:14.960
RYAN CHILCOTE: So the two logical options
are, one, that the U.K. chooses to pursue

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:16.750
a new deal with the European Union.

00:07:16.750 --> 00:07:21.360
Now, right now, the E.U. is saying they're
not going to renegotiate the exit terms.

00:07:21.360 --> 00:07:27.990
However, the E.U. would love if the U.K. came
back with a softer Brexit, if they wanted

00:07:27.990 --> 00:07:33.639
to leave the E.U., but have a closer relationship
after that with the European Union.

00:07:33.639 --> 00:07:37.849
That would require the prime minister to reach
across party lines, if you will, to the leader

00:07:37.849 --> 00:07:43.289
of the opposition, Jeremy Corbyn, and do some
kind of deal that they have already said that

00:07:43.289 --> 00:07:45.729
they would support, a softer Brexit.

00:07:45.729 --> 00:07:47.370
That seems pretty difficult to imagine.

00:07:47.370 --> 00:07:49.830
You know, they really don't like one another.

00:07:49.830 --> 00:07:54.800
There isn't that kind of bipartisan love,
if you will, to see something like that happen.

00:07:54.800 --> 00:07:58.879
The other option is that this goes back to
the British people, a second referendum.

00:07:58.879 --> 00:08:05.110
They could be asked, do you support the prime
minister's deal that she reached with the

00:08:05.110 --> 00:08:06.189
European Union?

00:08:06.189 --> 00:08:10.560
Obviously, it's just been rejected by the
Parliament, but the people would be asked.

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:16.370
Or do you think the U.K., in fact, now that
we know what we know, should remain in the

00:08:16.370 --> 00:08:17.870
European Union?

00:08:17.870 --> 00:08:20.310
Those are really the only two options on the
table -- Judy.

00:08:20.310 --> 00:08:23.349
JUDY WOODRUFF: The drama continues.

00:08:23.349 --> 00:08:25.370
Ryan Chilcote, reporting for us from London,
thank you, Ryan.

00:08:25.370 --> 00:08:26.430
RYAN CHILCOTE: Thank you.

00:08:26.430 --> 00:08:31.490
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we continue our look at
today's vote and where the U.K. goes from

00:08:31.490 --> 00:08:34.219
here with Sir Peter Westmacott.

00:08:34.219 --> 00:08:39.400
He had a 40-year career in the British Diplomatic
Service and he served as his country's ambassador

00:08:39.400 --> 00:08:41.150
to the United States.

00:08:41.150 --> 00:08:43.870
Sir Peter Westmacott, welcome back to the
"NewsHour."

00:08:43.870 --> 00:08:49.850
So, what does today's Parliament vote, rejecting
this latest plan, what does it mean for the

00:08:49.850 --> 00:08:52.700
prospects of Britain leaving the E.U.?

00:08:52.700 --> 00:08:54.839
Is it now more likely or less likely?

00:08:54.839 --> 00:08:59.410
PETER WESTMACOTT, Former British Ambassador
to the United States: Well, we are now in

00:08:59.410 --> 00:09:03.990
a state of some political meltdown, as your
correspondent was just explaining.

00:09:03.990 --> 00:09:09.700
I think at the moment it means that it is
less likely that we leave on the 29th of March,

00:09:09.700 --> 00:09:16.440
as scheduled, because of today's vote, which
was resoundingly against Theresa May's package,

00:09:16.440 --> 00:09:21.310
but also because, tomorrow, parliamentarians
are very likely to vote heavily against the

00:09:21.310 --> 00:09:23.380
idea of leaving with no deal.

00:09:23.380 --> 00:09:27.421
So, if you haven't got Theresa May's deal,
and you haven't got no deal, then what have

00:09:27.421 --> 00:09:28.421
you got?

00:09:28.421 --> 00:09:32.800
Answer, on the third day, on Thursday, there
will be a vote about whether to ask for an

00:09:32.800 --> 00:09:37.060
extension of the 29th of March deadline from
the European Commission.

00:09:37.060 --> 00:09:41.040
And at the moment, that is what is most likely
to happen in the near future.

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:45.680
So I think leaving on the 29th of March is
feeling a little less likely than it was before

00:09:45.680 --> 00:09:46.680
tonight's vote.

00:09:46.680 --> 00:09:51.550
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, you're saying parliamentarians
tomorrow likely to say, OK, we need some kind

00:09:51.550 --> 00:09:56.140
of deal if we're going the leave, the question
is, what does it look like?

00:09:56.140 --> 00:10:00.970
PETER WESTMACOTT: Well, it's not even as clear
as that, I'm afraid, Judy.

00:10:00.970 --> 00:10:05.709
What the parliamentarians will like say is,
we don't like the idea of what is crashing

00:10:05.709 --> 00:10:09.690
out with no deal, because it would be chaotic
in a whole lot of different ways.

00:10:09.690 --> 00:10:12.990
And neither the European Union nor the United
Kingdom is ready for that.

00:10:12.990 --> 00:10:16.440
But what they're not saying is what they would
like, and that's part of the prime minister's

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:17.520
frustration.

00:10:17.520 --> 00:10:22.300
She rushed off to Strasbourg over the weekend
to try and put a few improvements to her package,

00:10:22.300 --> 00:10:26.190
but, unfortunately, without checking first
with her own law officer, the attorney general,

00:10:26.190 --> 00:10:28.010
thought that the package would do the trick.

00:10:28.010 --> 00:10:32.470
And he then opined this morning, saying it
doesn't give the legal guarantees that she

00:10:32.470 --> 00:10:34.209
had hoped for.

00:10:34.209 --> 00:10:37.560
And so result was the Parliament said, this
isn't good enough.

00:10:37.560 --> 00:10:39.910
So we're a bit stuck in that sense.

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:45.730
The most likely thing, therefore, is extending
the timetable, if the European side will agree.

00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:50.720
And a lot of the signs today -- this evening
-- since the vote, are that the European Commission

00:10:50.720 --> 00:10:55.440
and the European member states are not giving
this away for nothing, that they will have

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:58.250
their own views as to how long the extension
might be.

00:10:58.250 --> 00:11:02.079
And there may be some conditions that are
not to the liking of the United Kingdom.

00:11:02.079 --> 00:11:06.209
So you could still end up crashing out, but
it feels to me it is not so likely that it

00:11:06.209 --> 00:11:11.389
will happen on the 29th of March because there
is likely to be a vote for an extension, if

00:11:11.389 --> 00:11:13.590
the Europeans agree to it, on Thursday.

00:11:13.590 --> 00:11:18.829
JUDY WOODRUFF: Peter Westmacott, why has this
been so messy and so difficult?

00:11:18.829 --> 00:11:21.880
What's at the core of what's going on here?

00:11:21.880 --> 00:11:29.410
PETER WESTMACOTT: The core of it, Judy, is
that it was always going to be very, very

00:11:29.410 --> 00:11:30.420
difficult.

00:11:30.420 --> 00:11:33.400
You can decide if you have got a box of eggs
in front of you whether you want to scramble

00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:35.390
them, fry them, poach them or whatever it
is.

00:11:35.390 --> 00:11:39.790
But once you have scrambled them, unscrambling
eggs is really difficult and a hard thing

00:11:39.790 --> 00:11:40.790
to do.

00:11:40.790 --> 00:11:43.019
And many of us, of course, said that at the
time.

00:11:43.019 --> 00:11:45.970
But fast-forward to the results of the referendum.

00:11:45.970 --> 00:11:50.750
But one of the problems is that Theresa May
decided that, in order to get herself a fresh

00:11:50.750 --> 00:11:55.529
mandate and a bigger majority, she would hold
a general election, when she didn't need to,

00:11:55.529 --> 00:11:57.389
18 months or so ago.

00:11:57.389 --> 00:11:59.130
And she lost her majority with it.

00:11:59.130 --> 00:12:03.410
And so now she's totally dependent on getting
any business done in the House of Commons

00:12:03.410 --> 00:12:06.920
on 10 votes from Northern Irish members of
Parliament.

00:12:06.920 --> 00:12:11.850
And, frankly, it's clear that if the law officer
this morning, if the attorney general had

00:12:11.850 --> 00:12:17.079
said it was OK legally, probably, those 10
Democratic Unionist Party M.P.s would have

00:12:17.079 --> 00:12:23.600
said, we can live with it, and probably enough
of the Conservative Brexiteers would have

00:12:23.600 --> 00:12:25.110
gone along with it as well.

00:12:25.110 --> 00:12:30.670
So she is somewhat held hostage by these 10
votes in Northern Ireland because of the fact

00:12:30.670 --> 00:12:32.790
that she lost her majority earlier on.

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:37.770
So that's made the government's position politically
extremely fragile all the way through.

00:12:37.770 --> 00:12:42.620
Added to that, I think the Conservative Party,
never mind the majority, or the lack of, has

00:12:42.620 --> 00:12:47.110
had real difficulty working out amongst themselves
what sort of Brexit they want.

00:12:47.110 --> 00:12:51.380
They have been riven in two, indecisive, unable
to sort things out.

00:12:51.380 --> 00:12:55.390
And so there's been a great deal of muddle
over the last 2.5 years, to the frustration,

00:12:55.390 --> 00:12:57.540
I have to say, of a lot of the British people.

00:12:57.540 --> 00:13:01.980
JUDY WOODRUFF: And is that any one person's
fault, or is it just the fault of the system?

00:13:01.980 --> 00:13:07.420
PETER WESTMACOTT: Well, you can point the
finger of blame on lots of people.

00:13:07.420 --> 00:13:11.100
You can point the finger of blame, if you
wish to, at David Cameron for having called

00:13:11.100 --> 00:13:15.280
the referendum in the first place, thinking
that he'd be able to win it if it happened.

00:13:15.280 --> 00:13:18.330
You can point the finger of blame, if you
want to, to the prime minister, because she

00:13:18.330 --> 00:13:23.140
is the head of the government which has conducted
these negotiations, to no avail, over the

00:13:23.140 --> 00:13:24.819
last 2.5, three years.

00:13:24.819 --> 00:13:29.839
Or you can point the finger of blame to some
very hard-line Brexiteers, who promised a

00:13:29.839 --> 00:13:33.649
certain number of things at the time of the
referendum and afterwards which turned out

00:13:33.649 --> 00:13:35.649
to be neither true nor deliverable.

00:13:35.649 --> 00:13:40.310
And they have hung in there, making the prime
minister's life really extremely difficult.

00:13:40.310 --> 00:13:43.610
So -- and you can probably think of a whole
lot of other people who you can blame for

00:13:43.610 --> 00:13:44.610
it.

00:13:44.610 --> 00:13:45.720
Some people would say the commission are being
intransigent.

00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:50.120
I don't actually buy that, because it was
the British people who asked to leave.

00:13:50.120 --> 00:13:51.920
And we're the ones who brought this upon ourselves.

00:13:51.920 --> 00:13:56.000
And we asked for this Irish backstop, which
is the proximate cause of the defeat of the

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:57.190
prime minister's package.

00:13:57.190 --> 00:13:59.000
And then we ask for it to be changed.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.990
So I think it's a little harsh to say that
the people in Brussels have been inflexible.

00:14:02.990 --> 00:14:07.440
JUDY WOODRUFF: And just very quickly, finally,
why should the rest of the world pay close

00:14:07.440 --> 00:14:12.529
attention to this, the United States, the
rest of the global economy?

00:14:12.529 --> 00:14:18.019
PETER WESTMACOTT: I think it matters to the
United States for two principal reasons.

00:14:18.019 --> 00:14:22.690
One is that the United Kingdom is a very business-friendly
economy, which is the obvious port of entry,

00:14:22.690 --> 00:14:26.209
especially for English-speaking peoples, to
the European single market.

00:14:26.209 --> 00:14:30.459
And we have had lots of inward investment
from companies building in the U.K., investing

00:14:30.459 --> 00:14:32.610
in the U.K. to get access to the E.U.

00:14:32.610 --> 00:14:37.930
And if that is taken away by the terms of
the Brexit deal and -- or no deal, that will

00:14:37.930 --> 00:14:38.930
be a problem.

00:14:38.930 --> 00:14:43.579
Secondly, I think the United Kingdom in the
European Union is a force, if you like, for

00:14:43.579 --> 00:14:45.660
the anglophone world.

00:14:45.660 --> 00:14:50.449
It has been a means of trying to ensure that
some of America's points of view, policies,

00:14:50.449 --> 00:14:53.449
preferences are transmitted to the European
Union.

00:14:53.449 --> 00:14:56.769
And I think that could be lost when we leave,
how we leave.

00:14:56.769 --> 00:14:59.649
And, thirdly, I think the European Union itself
is weakened.

00:14:59.649 --> 00:15:01.269
Of course, I would say this, wouldn't I?

00:15:01.269 --> 00:15:04.180
but I hear it from my French and German and
other friends.

00:15:04.180 --> 00:15:08.050
If the U.K. is no longer there, and the only
two big powers in the European Union are France

00:15:08.050 --> 00:15:12.070
and Germany, who often find it difficult to
agree on things, then I think the European

00:15:12.070 --> 00:15:13.070
Union is weaker.

00:15:13.070 --> 00:15:15.819
And the people who are rubbing their hands
are the people who are in the Kremlin.

00:15:15.819 --> 00:15:19.250
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, we are watching it all
very closely.

00:15:19.250 --> 00:15:21.930
Peter Westmacott, we thank you.

00:15:21.930 --> 00:15:28.250
JUDY WOODRUFF: In the day's other news: The
European Union and a growing list of nations

00:15:28.250 --> 00:15:34.420
banned flights by Boeing's 737 MAX, after
an air disaster in Ethiopia.

00:15:34.420 --> 00:15:38.839
Sunday's crash left all 157 people on board
dead.

00:15:38.839 --> 00:15:43.870
In the U.S., Boeing defended the plane, and
the Federal Aviation Administration maintained

00:15:43.870 --> 00:15:45.470
it is fit to fly.

